<h2>Solar Panels in Illinois</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>

<p>Illinois receives approximately 1,450-1,550 kWh per square meter annually of solar irradiance, placing it in the moderate-to-good category for solar energy production nationwide. The state experiences peak solar production during May through August, when daily irradiance levels can exceed 6-7 kWh per square meter. This seasonal pattern aligns well with peak air conditioning demands, allowing solar systems to offset the highest energy consumption periods effectively. Northern Illinois, including the Chicago metropolitan area, receives slightly less solar irradiance than central and southern regions, but the difference is minimal enough that solar remains highly viable throughout the state.</p>

<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in Illinois can be expected to produce approximately 7,200-8,400 kWh annually, depending on system orientation, tilt, and local shading conditions. South-facing installations with optimal 30-35 degree tilts achieve the highest production levels, though southeast and southwest orientations typically perform within 90-95% of optimal. The state's relatively flat terrain and agricultural landscape mean that most residential installations face minimal shading issues, contributing to consistent system performance across different locations.</p>

<p>Seasonal production variations in Illinois are notable, with summer months producing 40-50% more energy than winter months. December and January typically see the lowest production, while June and July achieve peak output. This seasonal variation actually benefits homeowners, as the highest solar production coincides with peak cooling demands and highest electricity rates during summer months. Modern solar installations in Illinois typically maintain 85-90% of their original production capacity after 20 years, ensuring long-term energy savings and return on investment.</p>

