<h2>Illinois Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Illinois offers comprehensive incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated fees, providing substantial savings for Illinois homeowners. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if the homeowner's tax liability is insufficient to claim the full credit in the installation year.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit applies to the complete solar installation cost, including panels, inverters, mounting systems, electrical work, and permits. For a typical \$20,000 system, this represents \$6,000 in federal tax savings. The credit has no income limitations and can be combined with other state and local incentives for maximum savings.</li>

<li><strong>Illinois Shines Program:</strong> This state-sponsored solar incentive program provides Solar Renewable Energy Credits (SRECs) that can be sold for additional income over 15 years. Current SREC values range from \$25-45 per megawatt-hour produced, adding \$150-400 annually for typical residential systems. The program also includes specific incentives for low-income households and community solar projects.</li>

<li><strong>ComEd Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> ComEd offers rebates up to \$1,500 for high-efficiency HVAC systems, smart thermostats, and energy-efficient appliances. Their Home Energy Assessment program provides free energy audits and customized recommendations, often identifying 20-30% potential energy savings through efficiency improvements.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Municipal utilities throughout Illinois offer varying rebate programs for solar installations and efficient HVAC systems. Many provide additional rebates of \$300-1,000 for Energy Star certified equipment, heat pump installations, and smart home energy management systems.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Illinois exempts solar installations from property tax assessments, ensuring that added home value from solar systems doesn't increase annual property tax obligations. This exemption applies to both the solar equipment and installation costs, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime.</li>
</ul>

<p>To maximize available incentives, Illinois homeowners should work with certified installers familiar with current programs and application processes. Many incentives require pre-approval or specific equipment certifications, making professional guidance essential for accessing all available savings opportunities.</p>

